 nation, Acting Egyptian examines the ways in which elites and effendis, men and women, used newly built performance spaces to debate morality, politics, and the implications of modernity. Drawing on scripts, playbills, ads, and numerous other sources, the book brings to life provocative debates that fostered a new image of national culture and performances that echoed the events of urban life in the struggle for independence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aTheater and statezEgyptzCairoxHistoryy19th century. 0aTheater and statezEgyptzCairoxHistoryy20th century. 0aTheaterzEgyptzCairoxHistoryy19th century. 0aTheaterzEgyptzCairoxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31918540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477319192423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477319192/original  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK